Rabbit Stew:
>1) Brown the rabbit (optional). Heat 1 tablespoon of olive oil in a Dutch oven over medium heat. Once hot, add the whole or pieced 3-pound rabbit and sear it on all sides if desired.
>2) Deglaze the pan. Add 2 cups of chopped celery, 2 teaspoons of garlic, 2-3 sliced shallots, 1 teaspoon of seasoned salt, 1 teaspoon salt, ¼ teaspoon pepper, and 2 bay leaves, then deglaze the pan with 1 cup of dry white wine. Allow the white wine to be reduced by half before adding the remaining vegetables.
>3) Simmer. Once the wine has reduced, add 2 cups of sliced carrots, 1 ½ pounds of cut potatoes, and 8 cups of broth. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat, cover, and simmer for 2 hours.
>4) Shred the meat. Pull the rabbit from the stew to remove the bones and shred the meat. The meat should fall from the bone very easily. Return the meat to the stew and discard the bones.
>5) Make a slurry. In a small bowl, combine ¼ cup of flour and â cup of cold water. Stir until all lumps have dissolved.
>6) Serve. Stir the flour slurry into the broth. Continue simmering and stirring until the stew has thickened. Then remove from heat and serve immediately.

I've eaten rabbit several times before. In stews mostly. It's almost like chicken but much gamier. Wild and stringy. There are many small bones in the rabbit, 40 or 50 bones in a big serving. Often people will fish them out with their fingers while the meat is partially in their mouths.
Alternatively you can separate the meat from bone with just your tongue and spit the bones onto a plate, and with the meat isolated you can spoon up some softened carrots, potatoes and greens from the stew and add it to your mouth for all of the flavors.

What's important is that you spit all of the bones out before swallowing.

Yeah, I've been there before.
This is a bit more specific advice for this problem in particular, but if you're having trouble drawing something like proper foot anatomy, try studying how other artists do it. Basically just pick an image you like from another artist and try emulating it for yourself. You won't be able to replicate it 1:1 at first, but eventually you'll get better at drawing whatever it is your trying to draw. I did this to learn how to draw paws better, and it worked fairly well for me, even though I'm still not perfect.
Also, you should probably take a break if you're this close to burning yourself out.

It’s pretty rough some times. You can learn, and you can draw. It’s not always easy, and sometimes your frustration feels much bigger than the enjoyment is. And sure, it’s extra hard if you’re in pain or had a rough day, etc., but somehow it’s still worth doing it.

The ups may not come so soon if you’re new, new, and the downs never truly leave. See: my bitching, which I’ll say I’m sorry for because I usually don’t let frustrations with pieces leak into the thread. Negativity breeds more negativity, so it’s something you have to actively fight against. But drawing is so rewarding, there’s something special about creation alone and especially if it pleases the audience.
